  1. HDanke Skeletron Prime

    Start a Conversation
    Aim: Creating a fully functional PRNG within terraria

    Notes:
    • Can use something random which can be recorded , without player interaction
    • - Only Mob behaviour can be recorded, the only issue is that there's nothing random in their behaviour, nothing.
    • Must be fast enough to be reliable, no one would want to wait 10 minutes to get an answer.
    Possible approaches:
    • The usage of a more advanced computer in order to calculate the result, this is by far the slowest.
    • Usage of a algorithm, controlled by a key, in order to scramble a number, the main issue is that it'll eventually scramble a number until it gets in a loop.
    • Anything else that can yeld a random output (preferably a binary output)
     
    HDanke, Dec 28, 2014 Report

  2. ZeroGravitas The Destroyer

    Start a Conversation
    The existing way to do a yes/no randomisation is to use door opening: it's 50% for either way. An assembly with birds then allows this state to be read dynamically (they either get though of not). Was used in this game shown on old forum: "Jokenpoo". Mechanism itself possibly shown better elsewhere (could not find).

    I've thought up a skeleton based variation, but not tried it out. It would have them walking up to a door with a plate that will close it from one side only, so 50% they will get blocked. (Not worked out further details yet.)

    Can't think of a hoik speed version of this using a door. But you could have the play manually stop a hoik engine that will then be in one of 2 states, as good as a coin toss. Obviously a series of randomisations can then be interpreted as a binary number and converted using something like Diceman's machine.

  18. Niranufoti Plantera

    Start a Conversation
    ZeroGravitas said: ↑
    The "rand" function is definitely called to determine which direction to flip the door ("1" or "-1"), but I'm unclear on how that inference is made, and what that mean. Pressumably it isn't re-seeding the RNG, so it's determinstic, but should presumably only repeat on a long time scale...?
    Click to expand...
    Yup, Main.rand is a System.Random object which is created when the game is started and while the game is running, it's not re-seeded (maybe it is when leaving a world/joining a new one, not sure about that), so you could theoretically predict the next random event. And as with all kinds of random random things, it can of course happen that some kind of pattern repeats sometimes, but in this door configuration, I don't see any patterns.
    Whether the door is flipped right (1) or left (-1) is decided by these lines:
    Code:
    int direction = 1;
if (Main.rand.Next(2) == 0)
	direction = -1;
    direction is set to 1 first. Then a random check is performed to find out whether or not to set direction to -1 instead (int System.Random.Next(int maxValue) returns a whole number that is at least 0 and less than maxValue, so Main.rand.Next(2) returns either 0 or 1).
     
    No, I'm not really the person to compliment your suggestions, that's what the "Like"-button is for. I only hand out semi-constructive criticism.
    ZeroGravitas likes this.
